-- Thompson Publishing Files Bankruptcy to Sell Assets With PNC as Top Bidder
-- B y   M i c h a e l   B a t h o n
-- 2010-09-21T23:58:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-21/thompson-publishing-holding-co-seeks-bankruptcy-protection-in-delaware.html
Thompson Publishing Holding Co.
Inc., which produces books on regulatory trends and how they 
affect businesses and government, sought bankruptcy protection
from creditors with an agreement to sell virtually all its
assets.  The company, based in Washington, listed debt of as much as
$500 million and assets of as much as $50 million in Chapter 11
documents filed today in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Wilmington,
Delaware. Six affiliates also filed for bankruptcy.  Thompson, which didn’t give a reason for the filing, has an
agreement with PNC Bank NA to act as the stalking-horse, or lead
bidder, to buy substantially all its assets for an undisclosed
price, court paper show. PNC also has agreed to provide the
company with as much as $3 million to help fund its operations
while in bankruptcy.  Derek C. Abbott, an attorney for the company, wasn’t
immediately able to respond to a phone call seeking comment
after regular business hours today.  The company publishes books, newsletters, audio
conferences, web products and e-mail alerts to help customers
with “the dynamic regulatory mandates facing their
organizations,” according to its  website . The publications
cover regulatory and compliance related issues in areas such as
education, energy, environment and health care.  Thompson is majority owned by Avista Capital Partners,
which bought a 50 percent stake in the company for $130 million
in 2006.  The case is In re Thompson Publishing Holding Co. Inc.,
10-13070, U.S. Bankruptcy Court, District of Delaware
(Wilmington).  To contact the reporter on this story:
Michael Bathon in Wilmington, Delaware, at 
 mbathon@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Rovella at   drovella@bloomberg.net . 